Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Sadeko Daniel¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset with information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for Just a month in the year 2019. It countains about 183,000 rides with information about their starting and ending location, the duration of the rides and the rider's infromation.

Structure of the dataset¶

There are 183412 bike rides for the year 2019 in the month of Febraury in the dataset with 16 columns Most of the data are numeric in nature with the others being categorical (user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for all_trip)

Data Wrangling¶

The dataset does not look entriely clean for to explore, thus, i will be performing some data wrangling on the dataset and doing data engineering to get most out of the data for to explore

Converting the duration in seconds to minutes¶

In [26]:
# Converting the duration in second to minutes to better get a definition of th duraton spend for a ride.
def convert_to_min(sec):
    """
    takes in an integer as input.
    Converts the seconds to minutes
    Returns an integer.
    """
    return int(sec/60)
gobike["duration_min"] = gobike["duration_sec"].apply(convert_to_min)

Calculating the distance between the start and end station location¶

In [30]:
# Using the great circle or the Orthodromic distance to get the distance
# using the latitudes and logitudes of the start and end station location

from math import radians, cos, sin,asin, sqrt, atan2
def distance_cal(cols):
    
    """
    This function calculates the distance given a starting latitude and logitude
    and ending latitude and logitude in a list as inputs.
    It uses the Great circle or Orthodromic distance formula.
    It returns the distance in 2 d.p
    
    """
    r = 6373
    start_lat = cols[0]
    start_long = cols[1]
    end_lat = cols[2]
    end_long = cols[3]
    
    start_lat, start_long, end_lat, end_long = (radians(start_lat),radians(start_long),radians(end_lat),radians(end_long))
    

    dist_lat = end_lat - start_lat
    dist_long = end_long - start_long
    
    a = sin(dist_lat/2)**2 + cos(start_lat)*cos(end_lat)*sin(dist_long/2)**2
    
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1-a))
    
    return round((c*r),2)

gobike["distance"] = gobike[["start_station_latitude","start_station_longitude",
                           "end_station_latitude","end_station_longitude"]].apply(distance_cal,axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183215 bike rides for the year 2019 in the dataset with 16 columns but with feature engineering on the start_time and end_time to get the year,month, day and hour, finally making a total of 22 features best to describe the dataset.. Most of the data are numeric in nature with the others being categorical (user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for all_trip).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in features that tell the duration of bike rides and features that can affect the duration of bike rides

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the distance betweeen the start and end of the bike ride should strongly affect the duration of bike ride: the longer the distance the longer the time taken to finish the ride.. I also think that gender, user_type, member_birth_year (older people might take a longer time).. will have effects on the duration of bike ride..

# This is a long tailed distribution skewed to the right, performing a log transformation on the data

plt.xscale("log")
plt.xticks([1,3,5,10,30,50,100,300,500,1000], ["1","3","5","10","30","50","100","300","500","1000"])
plt.xlabel('Minutes')
plt.show()

The duration of ride is a long tailed distribution skewed to the right, with majority of the with a low duration, to get a better understanding of the data and how it distributed, performing a log transformation on the data, it is seen that about 80% of the rides range from 3 to 25 minutes...

Conclusions¶

Analyzing this dataset has been an awesome journey if i may say, starting with identifying the main feature (the duration_min feature), I found out that the average trip usually takes about 5 to 25 minutes after performing a log transformation on the data. Also, most rides were taken during early morning hours around 7 am to 9am, with most rides around Teusdays and Thursdays.There was also a fair relationship between the duration for the ride and the distance taken, other factors that might have affected this relationship were analyzed.

I found out that the days had an effect on the duration of ride, During the Weekends longer rides are usually taken than weekdays and also older people took longer duration of ride than the younger ones. With further analysis, i found out that non-subscribers took longer rides during the weekends than the subscribers.
